[Student "S"]
{Your first bid is easy, you say 1\H. But what do you say after partner's 2\H response? 

You have 18 points and partner has 6-10. Doing the math, you total 24-28.

You want to make a bid that will tell partner to bid game if he has 9-10, but will stop at 3\H if he only has 6-7. Lots of players will bid 3\H with this hand to make just that invitation. There's nothing wrong with that bid.

But there is an improvement. Bid 3\C instead. Partner knows you aren't showing him a \C suit, why would you do that after agreeing on \Hs? What it means is "Partner I'm inviting you to bid the game if you have maximum, but if your decision is close decide based on \Cs, the suit I could use help in." It is called a <b>HELP SUIT GAME TRY</b>. Partner has 8 points and the \CA and decides that is enough to bid game.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \SK.

<b>North plays 4\H. East leads the \SK.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 2 : Total = 4

You win the \SA and pull trumps in three rounds. You need to manufacture one winner and you can see right off the bat that it cannot be manufactured in \Ds or \Cs. However, you <b>CAN</b> set up the \S8.

Lead the \ST. East must win with his \SJ. Let's say he plays a \C. Win with dummy's \CA and play the \S9, discarding a small \C. East will take his \SQ and cash a \C trick, but then must let you back in. You enter dummy with the \DA and discard your \D loser on the good \S8.

It is extra nice when the opponents hand you a contract.

You cannot make 10 tricks unless East's opening lead is a \S. }
[Play "W"]SK

